---
category: Capability
expires: 2021-12-31 (6 months from now)
---

# Introduction to the role of Solution architect

A solution architect provides technical vision, solution leadership and architectural design.

## Skills required to be a Solution architect

- Understanding the whole context
- Bridging the gap between the technical and non-technical
- Turning business problems into solution designs
- Solution design
- Digital perspective
- Community collaboration
- Commercial understanding

## Understanding the whole context

- The ability to look beyond the immediate problem and identify the wider implications.
-	Understands relevant historical context and future impact.
- Understands how current work fits in broader contexts and strategies.
- Looks for deeper underlying problems and opportunities.

### Capability requirement

### Awareness

- You can understand how your work supports your team and identify wider influences and how they apply.
- You can keep an open mind and understand the broader context.

### Working

- You can understand trends and practices outside your team and how these will effect your work.
- You understand how your work fits into the brader strategy and historical context.
- You understand information context and integration requirements within your team and how they will impact your work.

### Practitioner

Provide evidence that 

- You can understand trends and practices within the DfE and how they will impact on your work.
- You look for deeper underlying problems and opportunities.
- You understand information context and integration requirements within the broader organisation and how they will impact your work.

### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You can understand trends and practicies outside the DfE and they will impact your work.
- You can anticipate changing policy and trends in industry.
- You can understand information context and integration requirements outside the organisation and how this impacts the DfE.

## Bridging the gap between the technical and the non-technical

- Able to communicate effectively across organisational, technical and political boundaries, understanding the context.
- Simplify complex and technical information by using appropriate and accessible language for non-technical audiences.
- Able to advocate and communicate what a team does to create trust and authenticity and can respond to challenge.

### Capability requirement

### Awareness

- You are aware of the need to translate technical concepts into non-technical language.
- You understand what communication is required to internal and external stakeholders.

### Working

- You can communicate effectively with technical and non-technical stakeholders.
- You can facilitate discussions within a multidisciplinary team
- You can advocate for your team externally and can manage differing perspectives.

### Practitioner

Provide evidence that 

- You can identify needs of business and technical stakeholders.
- You can effectively manage stakeholderâ€™s expectations.
- You have excellent communication skills, particularly relating to brokering difficult conversations / negotiations.

### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You can broker relationships with stakeholders at all levels.
- You can facilitate discussions across high-risk or complex topics, or under constrained timescales.
- You can manage stakeholder expectations.
- You can speak and represent the profession to audiences inside and outside of government.

## Turning business problems into solution designs

- The ability to work with business and technology stakeholders to translate business problems into solution designs.
- Creates an optimal design through an iterative process, aligning the user need with the solution requirements and organisational objectives.

### Capability requirement

### Working

- You can design solutions characterised by managed levels of risk, manageable business and technical complexity and meaningful impact.
- You can work with well-understood technology and identifies appropriate patterns.

### Practitioner

Provide evidence that 

- You can understand trends and practices within the broader organisation and how these will impact your work.
- You can look for deeper underlying problems and opportunities.
- You can anticipate problems before they occur and identify the impact of changes to policy.
- You can understand information context and integration requirements within the broader organisation and how these will impact your work.
- You can shape the business models and processes of the DfE.

### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You can understand trends and practices outside their organisation and how these will impact your work.
- You can anticipate changing policy and emerging trends in industry.
- You can understand information context and integration requirements outside the organisation and how this impacts the DfE.

## Solution design

- Explore different approaches to solving problems, applying technical knowledge and experience to create or design workable prototypes.
- Creates the specification and design of solutions to meet defined business and user needs.
- Able to visualise views and viewpoints to articulate the ideal service to meet user needs.

### Capability requirement

### Awareness

- You know what solution design is and why and when to use it.

### Working
- You know when to use solutions design to fill user need.
- You translate conceptual designs into logical designs and start to guide physical designs.
- You produces detailed designs and documents all work using required standards, methods and tools, including prototyping tools where appropriate.
- You design solutions characterised by managed levels of risk, manageable business and technical complexity and meaningful impact.
- You work with well-understood technology and identify appropriate patterns.

### Practitioner

Provide evidence that 

- You know a variety of solutions design techniques and choose the most appropriate ones.
- You design solutions characterised by medium levels of risk, impact and business or technical complexity.
- You select appropriate design standards, methods and tools and ensure they are applied effectively.
- You review the systems designs of others to ensure selection of appropriate technology, efficient use of resources and integration of multiple systems and technology.
- You work with well-understood technology and contribute to appropriate patterns.

### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You are experienced in using a variety of solution design techniques.
- You share best practice and can coach others.
- You design solutions characterised by high levels of risk, impact and business or technical complexity.
- You evolve solution design practice within an enterprise or industry architecture.
- You influence industry-based models for the development of new technology applications.
- You develop effective implementation and procurement strategies, consistent with business needs. 
- You Ensure adherence to relevant technical strategies, policies, standards and practices.

## Digital perspective

- Understands how the digital economy is changing user behaviour and the government landscape.
- Able to make informed decisions based on user needs, available technology and value for money.
- Have knowledge of the wider digital economy and advances in technology.

### Capability requirement

### Awareness

- You demonstrate an awareness of design, technology and data principles and how these fit into the cultural dialogue and relevant priorities.
- You understand the range of available technology choices.

### Working

- You are responsive to changes in technology, adapting their approach accordingly.
- You make decisions to meet user needs in the government context.
- You understand the importance of assisted digital and are able to design services and make decisions to meet user needs.

### Practitioner

Provide evidence that 

- You can apply a digital understanding to your work.
- You can identify and implement solutions for assisted digital.

### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You have knowledge of the wider digital economy and advances in technology, understanding how these impact on a government context.
- You make decisions that set the standards for others to follow.
- You understand working with agility at an organisational level and can create the environment for success.

## Community collaboration

- Contributes to the work of the community, building successful teams through understanding team styles and influencing as well as motivating team members.
- Gives and receives constructive feedback, facilitating the feedback loop.
- Facilitates conflict resolution within teams, ensures the team is transparent and that the work is understood externally.
- Help teams maintain a focus on delivery while being aware of the importance of professional development.

### Capability requirement

### Awareness
- You can understand the work of others and the importance of team dynamics, collaboration and feedback.

### Working

- You contribute to the work of others whilst having the ability to motivate and empower teams.
- You create the right environment for teams to work in and can facilitate the best team makeup depending on the situation.
- You recognise and deal with issues.

### Practitioner

Provide evidence that 

- You Work collaboratively within a group, actively networking with others and engaging in varying types of feedback choosing the appropriate time and ensuring the discussion sticks.
- You use initiative to identify problems or issues in the team dynamic and rectify them.
- You can pull out issues through agile health-checks with the team to provoke the right responses.

### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You can solve and unblock issues between teams or departments at the highest level.
- You understand the psychology of the team and have strong mediation skills.

## Commercial understanding

- Understand and contribute to commercial contracts, procurement and sourcing.
- Understand the importance of and contribute to a robust supplier selection and evaluation process to minimise the risk of delivery delays.
- Use government procurement processes and frameworks such as G-Cloud, Digital Services Framework and the Digital Marketplace.

### Capability requirement

### Working

- You can understand appropriate internal contacts and processes within a government department.
- You can understand different sourcing strategies and when to apply them.

## Practitioner

Provide evidence that 
- You can identify appropriate contractual frameworks.
- You can identify, evaluate and select appropriate suppliers.

Additionally:
  - Business case design.
  - Investment decisions.
  - Set the direction.
  
### Expert

Provide evidence that 

- You can lead a technical procurement from suggestion questions through to evaluation of bids and confirming all risks and issues.

